{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630983"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:21:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:21:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17341"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17341"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.76,0.09,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114331"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10031"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17341"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96331"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23490"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114331"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe arterial supply to the uterus is crucial for reproductive function and surgical planning.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the origin of the uterine artery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Branch of the external iliac artery","Branch of the anterior division of internal iliac artery","Branch of the common iliac artery","Branch of the posterior division of internal iliac artery","Branch of the ovarian artery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Euterine artery is a branch of the anterior division of the internal iliac artery\u003C/strong\u003E. It courses medially through the base of the broad ligament to reach the cervix, then ascends along the lateral margin of the uterus in a tortuous manner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eexternal iliac artery\u003C/strong\u003E primarily supplies the lower limbs and does not directly supply pelvic organs. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommon iliac artery\u003C/strong\u003E divides into internal and external iliac arteries and does not directly supply branches to pelvic organs. While the internal iliac artery does give rise to the uterine artery, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior division of internal iliac artery\u003C/strong\u003E does not give rise to the uterine artery as it is the anterior division that provides this branch. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eovarian artery\u003C/strong\u003E anastomoses with the uterine artery but does not give rise to it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe uterine artery forms an important anastomosis with the ovarian artery at the cornua of the uterus. It provides the main blood supply to the uterus, cervix, upper portion of the vagina, and supporting structures within the broad ligament.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The uterine artery is a branch of the anterior division of the internal iliac artery","The uterine artery anastomoses with the ovarian artery at the cornua of the uterus","The uterine artery supplies the uterus, cervix, upper vagina, and supporting structures in the broad ligament"],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur A. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":